<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The diagnostic shape of S2 is found in both males and females, leading us to believe that this is not an adaptation for housing the retracted ovipositor system, as can be found in some species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platygastridae" genus="Synopeas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Synopeas" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Synopeas</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Förster">Foerster</normalizedToken>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Platygaster" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Platygaster" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Platygaster</taxonomicName>
Latreille.
</paragraph>
